WEBVTT

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:09.120
Hi, I'm Hadley Wickham, the Chief Scientist at Posit, and for the purpose of this video,

00:00:09.120 --> 00:00:15.040
the Chief Maintainer of the purr package. So what is the purr package? It's kind of hard to

00:00:15.040 --> 00:00:20.320
describe what purr is to be honest, but to put it into words, I think I've got a pretty good sense

00:00:20.320 --> 00:00:26.480
of like what function feels like a purr function to me. But I think the best way to think of it is

00:00:26.480 --> 00:00:32.880
as a toolkit for help, for supporting like functional programming. What is functional

00:00:32.880 --> 00:00:37.360
programming? That's also kind of hard to explain, but the chief advantage is it gives you a bunch

00:00:37.360 --> 00:00:43.439
of tools for operating on vectors, or pairs of vectors, or triplets, or etc. of vectors,

00:00:43.439 --> 00:00:52.240
where you work on each individual element of the vector in isolation. And that allows you to

00:00:52.240 --> 00:00:57.200
apply a function to do something to each element, knowing that there's no way that the other other

00:00:57.200 --> 00:01:02.400
elements are going to affect the computation at all. So many of the functions of purr are

00:01:02.400 --> 00:01:07.760
alternatives to for loops. For loops are by any means like not a bad thing. You should never be

00:01:07.760 --> 00:01:12.239
embarrassed or ashamed of using a for loop. For loops are great because they're like very,

00:01:12.239 --> 00:01:16.400
very concrete. It's like very obvious what you're doing, because you're doing like,

00:01:16.400 --> 00:01:20.639
take this element and do this to it. Take that element and do that. And you can very easily

00:01:20.639 --> 00:01:26.720
think about like stepping through that. So the functions in purr, particularly the map functions,

00:01:27.279 --> 00:01:36.559
are kind of a step up in abstraction. And that step up is, it's a challenge, right? But I think

00:01:36.559 --> 00:01:43.040
there's some good reasons to do it. And the first one is it makes it easy to avoid, or ensures that

00:01:43.040 --> 00:01:48.720
you avoid some like performance bottlenecks with loops. Now for loops themselves are not slow,

00:01:49.279 --> 00:01:55.360
but if in your for loop it's easy to get to accidentally repeatedly modify or repeatedly

00:01:55.360 --> 00:02:00.400
extend a vector, then that can be slow. Although changes in the latest versions of argument are

00:02:00.400 --> 00:02:07.279
much less bad than it has been in the past. So performance, a little bit useful. I think one

00:02:07.839 --> 00:02:16.160
big advantage of switching to purr is that you can also switch to, it's not future,

00:02:17.119 --> 00:02:24.320
but the fur package. So the fur package is, has exactly the same syntax as purr,

00:02:25.039 --> 00:02:32.399
but it spreads the computation across multiple ports. So purr, because it guarantees that all

00:02:32.399 --> 00:02:37.360
of the computations are independent, much much easier to share that work across multiple ports.

00:02:39.119 --> 00:02:43.919
The other thing, particularly in this latest version of purr, is that it gives you a really,

00:02:44.160 --> 00:02:49.759
a access to a really powerful useful tool, and that's progress paths, which I'll talk about a

00:02:49.759 --> 00:02:54.880
little bit later. But purr, definitely kind of an advanced programming tool. You can go a very

00:02:54.880 --> 00:03:00.800
long way with for loops, but I think if you can master the map functions of purr, you can write

00:03:00.800 --> 00:03:07.279
code that is more succinct, more clear, and more likely to be correct the first time you write it.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:14.720
So today I'm going to talk about purr 1.0, and the 1.0 release of any package is pretty special,

00:03:14.720 --> 00:03:20.000
because it's kind of, this marks the package as at least like the initial development is kind of

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:26.800
done. This is a package that we are confident about, it's stable, and we expect it to be around

00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:32.479
for the long term. And for purr in particular, this is kind of an opportunity to take a look

00:03:32.479 --> 00:03:37.360
at it broadly, and say which of the functions in this package are really related to the core

00:03:37.360 --> 00:03:42.559
purpose of functional programming, of working with vectors and functions,

00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:48.399
and which functions of purr are not, and maybe need to be superseded or duplicated.

