most exciting feature, the coolest feature, is the new progress bar. So let's just make a little,

00:04:00.160 --> 00:04:05.279
very silly little example. Let's take a brief look at what life is like without progress bar.

00:04:05.279 --> 00:04:11.679
So let's just imagine we're going to map over 100 numbers, and in lieu of doing anything

00:04:11.679 --> 00:04:16.079
useful here, I'm just gonna, I'm just gonna sleep, I'm just gonna pause for a 10th of a second.

00:04:17.519 --> 00:04:22.239
So when I run this code, like I know something's working, I know this is going to take 10 seconds

00:04:22.239 --> 00:04:28.079
in total, but I'm getting like no feedback on what's going on. And for a real life job,

00:04:28.079 --> 00:04:32.559
you don't know exactly how long it's going to take, and you don't know when something's happening,

00:04:32.559 --> 00:04:36.959
like should you just take a deep breath, should you go grab a coffee, or should you come back

00:04:36.959 --> 00:04:43.279
tomorrow. So what's great now, in the latest version of purr, is you can say dot progress

00:04:43.279 --> 00:04:49.119
equals true, and get a convenient progress bar that tells you both how far through the process

00:04:49.119 --> 00:04:55.440
you are, and an estimated time till completion, assuming that every single iteration takes about

00:04:55.519 --> 00:04:59.279
the same amount of time. Now that alone, I think, is pretty great for interactive usage.

